#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:5
msgid "Reviewer guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:7
msgid ""
"Reviewing open pull requests (PRs) helps move the project forward. We "
"encourage people outside the project to get involved as well; it's a great "
"way to get familiar with the codebase."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:12
msgid "Who can be a reviewer?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:14
msgid ""
"Reviews can come from outside the NumPy team -- we welcome contributions "
"from domain experts (for instance, `linalg` or `fft`) or maintainers of "
"other projects. You do not need to be a NumPy maintainer (a NumPy team "
"member with permission to merge a PR) to review."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:19
msgid ""
"If we do not know you yet, consider introducing yourself in `the mailing "
"list or Slack <https://numpy.org/community/>`_ before you start reviewing "
"pull requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:23
msgid "Communication guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:25
msgid ""
"Every PR, good or bad, is an act of generosity. Opening with a positive "
"comment will help the author feel rewarded, and your subsequent remarks may "
"be heard more clearly. You may feel good also."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:28
msgid ""
"Begin if possible with the large issues, so the author knows they've been "
"understood. Resist the temptation to immediately go line by line, or to open "
"with small pervasive issues."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:31
msgid ""
"You are the face of the project, and NumPy some time ago decided `the kind "
"of project it will be <https://numpy.org/code-of-conduct/>`_: open, "
"empathetic, welcoming, friendly and patient. Be `kind <https://youtu.be/"
"tzFWz5fiVKU?t=49m30s>`_ to contributors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:35
msgid ""
"Do not let perfect be the enemy of the good, particularly for documentation. "
"If you find yourself making many small suggestions, or being too nitpicky on "
"style or grammar, consider merging the current PR when all important "
"concerns are addressed. Then, either push a commit directly (if you are a "
"maintainer) or open a follow-up PR yourself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:40
msgid ""
"If you need help writing replies in reviews, check out some :ref:`standard "
"replies for reviewing<saved-replies>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:44
msgid "Reviewer checklist"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:48
msgid ""
"Is the intended behavior clear under all conditions? Some things to watch:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:47
msgid ""
"What happens with unexpected inputs like empty arrays or nan/inf values?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:48
msgid "Are axis or shape arguments tested to be `int` or `tuples`?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:49
msgid "Are unusual `dtypes` tested if a function supports those?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:50
msgid "Should variable names be improved for clarity or consistency?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:51
msgid "Should comments be added, or rather removed as unhelpful or extraneous?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:52
msgid ""
"Does the documentation follow the :ref:`NumPy guidelines<howto-document>`? "
"Are the docstrings properly formatted?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:54
msgid ""
"Does the code follow NumPy's :ref:`Stylistic Guidelines<stylistic-"
"guidelines>`?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:55
msgid ""
"If you are a maintainer, and it is not obvious from the PR description, add "
"a short explanation of what a branch did to the merge message and, if "
"closing an issue, also add \"Closes gh-123\" where 123 is the issue number."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:58
msgid ""
"For code changes, at least one maintainer (i.e. someone with commit rights) "
"should review and approve a pull request. If you are the first to review a "
"PR and approve of the changes use the GitHub `approve review <https://help."
"github.com/articles/reviewing-changes-in-pull-requests/>`_ tool to mark it "
"as such. If a PR is straightforward, for example it's a clearly correct bug "
"fix, it can be merged straight away. If it's more complex or changes public "
"API, please leave it open for at least a couple of days so other maintainers "
"get a chance to review."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:66
msgid ""
"If you are a subsequent reviewer on an already approved PR, please use the "
"same review method as for a new PR (focus on the larger issues, resist the "
"temptation to add only a few nitpicks).  If you have commit rights and think "
"no more review is needed, merge the PR."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:72
msgid "For maintainers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:74
msgid ""
"Make sure all automated CI tests pass before merging a PR, and that the :ref:"
"`documentation builds <building-docs>` without any errors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:76
msgid ""
"In case of merge conflicts, ask the PR submitter to :ref:`rebase on main "
"<rebasing-on-main>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:78
msgid ""
"For PRs that add new features or are in some way complex, wait at least a "
"day or two before merging it. That way, others get a chance to comment "
"before the code goes in. Consider adding it to the release notes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:81
msgid ""
"When merging contributions, a committer is responsible for ensuring that "
"those meet the requirements outlined in the :ref:`Development process "
"guidelines <guidelines>` for NumPy. Also, check that new features and "
"backwards compatibility breaks were discussed on the `numpy-discussion "
"mailing list <https://mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/numpy-discussion>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:86
msgid ""
"Squashing commits or cleaning up commit messages of a PR that you consider "
"too messy is OK. Remember to retain the original author's name when doing "
"this. Make sure commit messages follow the :ref:`rules for NumPy <writing-"
"the-commit-message>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:90
msgid ""
"When you want to reject a PR: if it's very obvious, you can just close it "
"and explain why. If it's not, then it's a good idea to first explain why you "
"think the PR is not suitable for inclusion in NumPy and then let a second "
"committer comment or close."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:94
msgid ""
"If the PR submitter doesn't respond to your comments for 6 months, move the "
"PR in question to the inactive category with the “inactive” tag attached. At "
"this point, the PR can be closed by a maintainer. If there is any interest "
"in finalizing the PR under consideration, this can be indicated at any time, "
"without waiting 6 months, by a comment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:99
msgid ""
"Maintainers are encouraged to finalize PRs when only small changes are "
"necessary before merging (e.g., fixing code style or grammatical errors). If "
"a PR becomes inactive, maintainers may make larger changes. Remember, a PR "
"is a collaboration between a contributor and a reviewer/s, sometimes a "
"direct push is the best way to finish it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:106
msgid "API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:107
msgid ""
"As mentioned most public API changes should be discussed ahead of time and "
"often with a wider audience (on the mailing list, or even through a NEP)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:110
msgid ""
"For changes in the public C-API be aware that the NumPy C-API is backwards "
"compatible so that any addition must be ABI compatible with previous "
"versions. When it is not the case, you must add a guard."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:114
msgid "For example ``PyUnicodeScalarObject`` struct contains the following::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:116
msgid ""
"#if NPY_FEATURE_VERSION >= NPY_1_20_API_VERSION\n"
"    char *buffer_fmt;\n"
"#endif"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:120
msgid ""
"Because the ``buffer_fmt`` field was added to its end in NumPy 1.20 (all "
"previous fields remained ABI compatible). Similarly, any function added to "
"the API table in ``numpy/_core/code_generators/numpy_api.py`` must use the "
"``MinVersion`` annotation. For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:127
msgid "'PyDataMem_SetHandler':                 (304, MinVersion(\"1.22\")),"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:129
msgid ""
"Header only functionality (such as a new macro) typically does not need to "
"be guarded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:133
msgid "GitHub workflow"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:135
msgid ""
"When reviewing pull requests, please use workflow tracking features on "
"GitHub as appropriate:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:138
msgid ""
"After you have finished reviewing, if you want to ask for the submitter to "
"make changes, change your review status to \"Changes requested.\" This can "
"be done on GitHub, PR page, Files changed tab, Review changes (button on the "
"top right)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:142
msgid ""
"If you're happy about the current status, mark the pull request as Approved "
"(same way as Changes requested). Alternatively (for maintainers): merge the "
"pull request, if you think it is ready to be merged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:146
msgid ""
"It may be helpful to have a copy of the pull request code checked out on "
"your own machine so that you can play with it locally. You can use the "
"`GitHub CLI <https://docs.github.com/en/github/getting-started-with-github/"
"github-cli>`_ to do this by clicking the ``Open with`` button in the upper "
"right-hand corner of the PR page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:152
msgid ""
"Assuming you have your :ref:`development environment<development-"
"environment>` set up, you can now build the code and test it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:158
msgid "Standard replies for reviewing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:160
msgid ""
"It may be helpful to store some of these in GitHub's `saved replies <https://"
"github.com/settings/replies/>`_ for reviewing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:167
msgid "**Usage question**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:164
msgid ""
"You are asking a usage question. The issue tracker is for bugs and new "
"features.\n"
"I'm going to close this issue, feel free to ask for help via our [help "
"channels](https://numpy.org/gethelp/)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:172
msgid "**You’re welcome to update the docs**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:170
msgid ""
"Please feel free to offer a pull request updating the documentation if you "
"feel it could be improved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:178
msgid "**Self-contained example for bug**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:175
msgid ""
"Please provide a [self-contained example code](https://stackoverflow.com/"
"help/mcve), including imports and data (if possible), so that other "
"contributors can just run it and reproduce your issue.\n"
"Ideally your example code should be minimal."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:187
msgid "**Software versions**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:181
msgid ""
"To help diagnose your issue, please paste the output of:\n"
"```\n"
"python -c 'import numpy; print(numpy.version.version)'\n"
"```\n"
"Thanks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:194
msgid "**Code blocks**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:190
msgid ""
"Readability can be greatly improved if you [format](https://help.github.com/"
"articles/creating-and-highlighting-code-blocks/) your code snippets and "
"complete error messages appropriately.\n"
"You can edit your issue descriptions and comments at any time to improve "
"readability.\n"
"This helps maintainers a lot. Thanks!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:199
msgid "**Linking to code**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:197
msgid ""
"For clarity's sake, you can link to code like [this](https://help.github.com/"
"articles/creating-a-permanent-link-to-a-code-snippet/)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:206
msgid "**Better description and title**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:202
msgid ""
"Please make the title of the PR more descriptive.\n"
"The title will become the commit message when this is merged.\n"
"You should state what issue (or PR) it fixes/resolves in the description "
"using the syntax described [here](https://docs.github.com/en/github/managing-"
"your-work-on-github/linking-a-pull-request-to-an-issue#linking-a-pull-"
"request-to-an-issue-using-a-keyword)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:211
msgid "**Regression test needed**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:209
msgid ""
"Please add a [non-regression test](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-"
"regression_testing) that would fail at main but pass in this PR."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:216
msgid "**Don’t change unrelated**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../dev/reviewer_guidelines.rst:214
msgid ""
"Please do not change unrelated lines. It makes your contribution harder to "
"review and may introduce merge conflicts to other pull requests."
msgstr ""
